<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-038-289 </DOCNO><DOCID>11 414 851</DOCID><JOURNAL>Digital Review  Oct 7 1991 v8 n32 p69(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Cahners-Ziff Publishing Associates LP 1991.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Utility optimizes access to VAXcluster resources. (SystemManagement Software Inc. introduces Cluster Performance Masterutility program for VAXcluster computer program) (productannouncement)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Bowen, Ted Smalley.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   System Management Software Inc. (Product introduction).andO;Product:   Cluster Performance Management (Utility program) (Productintroduction).andO;Topic:     Product IntroductionUtility Programs.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>SIMI VALLEY, Calif.andP;  -- System Management Software (SMS) has announced a VMSutility for VAXclusters and local area VAXclusters that is designed to boostcluster performance by reducing the overhead associated with remote lockmastering.andM;The utility, called Cluster Performance Master (CPM), was codeveloped byTouch Technologies of San Diego and Software Perspectives of Simi Valley.andM;Lock masters are those nodes in a cluster that control synchronization of andaccess to resources, such as files, buffers, tapes and disks, according toSMS officials.andM;When nodes request resources that are located on other nodes, additionalCluster Interconnect traffic is generated by the remote lock requestsinvolved, officials said.andM;CPM monitors the frequency of requests for cluster resources and periodicallyreassigns lock master control, placing the lock for a particular resource onthe node that most often receives requests for it, according to the SMSofficials.andM;In a VAXcluster, lock master nodes are selected without reference to whichnodes receive most of the requests for individual resources.andM;&quot;VMS randomly assigns node responsibilities for monitoring resources.andP;  Eachnode request across the cluster takes 10 times longer than if that requestwere local.andP;  The more VAXes there are in a cluster, the higher the odds arethat the lock will be in the wrong place,&quot; said Dan Esbensen, TouchTechnologies' president.andM;CPM's Intelligent Remastering occurs as a background process.andM;CPM works on CI, NI and mixed interconnect clusters, according to Esbensen.andM;&quot;The technology was [not] trivial.andP;  We had to write the algorithms necessaryto perform the calculation of which resources are hit the most so that theywouldn't sap too much CPU.andP;  We also had to avoid the oscillation problemsthat can occur if the locks are constantly moved around.andP;  We use algorithmsthat dynamically adjust the thresholds for when things should be dynamicallyremastered,&quot; he said.andM;Cluster Performance Master is available now and is priced from $300 to $3,000depending on CPU size.andM;System Management Software Inc. can be contacted at 990 Enchanted Way, Suite105, Simi Valley, CA 93065, (805) 582-6151.andO;</TEXT></DOC>